  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How are the types of nerve cell structured?",
  "response": "Nerve cells, or neurons, are specialized cells responsible for transmitting information throughout the nervous system. Neurons have a distinct structure that allows them to perform this function effectively. Here are the main types of nerve cells and their structures:\n\n1. **Motor Neurons**:\n   - **Structure**: Motor neurons typically have a long axon that extends from the cell body to muscle fibers. They also have multiple dendrites that receive signals from other neurons.\n   - **Function**: These neurons carry signals from the central nervous system (CNS) to muscles and glands, causing them to contract or secrete.\n\n2. **Sensory Neurons**:\n   - **Structure**: Sensory neurons often have a unique structure with a long dendrite and a short axon. They can have specialized receptors at their ends for detecting stimuli (like light, sound, or touch).\n   - **Function**: They transmit sensory information from sensory receptors to the CNS.\n\n3. **Interneurons**:\n   - **Structure**: Interneurons generally have short axons and many dendrites. Their structure allows for complex connections with other neurons within the CNS.\n   - **Function**: They connect sensory and motor neurons and process information in the brain and spinal cord.\n\n**General Structure of Neurons**:\n1. **Cell Body (Soma)**: Contains the nucleus and organelles. It is responsible for the maintenance and metabolic processes of the neuron.\n2. **Dendrites**: Branch-like structures that receive signals from other neurons and convey this information to the cell body.\n3. **Axon**: A long, thin cable that transmits signals away from the cell body to other neurons or muscles. Axons can be myelinated (wrapped in a myelin sheath) to increase the speed of signal transmission.\n4. **Axon Terminals**: The ends of axons where neurotransmitters are released to communicate with other neurons or target cells.\n\n**Types of Neurons Based on Structure**:\n- **Unipolar Neurons**: Have a single process extending from the cell body, typically found in sensory ganglia.\n- **Bipolar Neurons**: Have two processes (one axon and one dendrite) and are often found in sensory systems like the retina.\n- **Multipolar Neurons**: Have one axon and multiple dendrites, the most common type found in the CNS, particularly in the brain and spinal cord.\n\nOverall, the structure of nerve cells is intricately designed to allow for efficient communication and processing of information in the nervous system.",
